3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates funding rates hourly based on the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices across its shared liquidity layer. Rates are settled automatically between long and short positions, with payments flowing through the protocol's cross-chain infrastructure. The shared order book model means funding rates reflect aggregated demand from multiple DEX frontends on NEAR and EVM chains."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","SUI","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI's status as a high-performance Layer 1 blockchain creates significant funding rate volatility during network developments and ecosystem growth phases. The pair's mid-tier volume on Orderly provides adequate liquidity for arbitrage while maintaining rate premiums that can exceed centralized exchange offerings."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"SUI/USDT funding rates on Orderly Network have shown distinct patterns tied to Sui blockchain milestones and DeFi adoption cycles. During major network upgrades or ecosystem announcements, funding rates frequently spike above 0.1% hourly as perpetual prices diverge from spot. The shared liquidity model tends to amplify these movements compared to isolated DEX pools. Monthly analysis shows funding rates correlate strongly with SUI's relative performance against other Layer 1 tokens, creating predictable arbitrage windows."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Chain Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly's multi-chain architecture enables unique arbitrage strategies between NEAR and EVM-based funding rates for the same SUI/USDT pair. Traders can exploit rate differentials when one frontend experiences higher demand than others sharing the order book. The 0.02% maker fee structure favors high-frequency funding rate arbitrage, while the shared liquidity reduces slippage risks. Cross-chain bridge delays can create temporary funding rate premiums lasting 2-4 hours."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The shared order book model introduces counterparty risks across multiple frontend partners that may not exist on standalone exchanges. Smart contract risks span both Orderly's core infrastructure and the various DEX frontends accessing the liquidity layer. SUI's price volatility can lead to rapid funding rate reversals, particularly during Asian trading hours when Layer 1 activity peaks. Position sizing should account for the complex liquidation mechanics across the multi-chain architecture."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Orderly Network's shared liquidity affect SUI funding rates?","answer":"The shared order book aggregates trading activity from multiple DEX frontends, creating more stable funding rate calculations than isolated pools. However, this can also amplify rate movements when large positions are opened across multiple frontends simultaneously."},{"question":"What are the optimal position sizes for SUI funding rate arbitrage on Orderly?","answer":"Given SUI's mid-tier volume, positions should typically range from $1,000-$10,000 to avoid significant market impact. The shared liquidity model supports larger positions than typical DEX pools, but monitoring across-chain activity is essential."},{"question":"How do Orderly's cross-chain mechanics impact funding rate timing?","answer":"Funding payments process hourly regardless of which frontend you use, but cross-chain position transfers may create temporary exposure during bridge confirmations. Plan entries/exits around the hourly funding schedule to maximize rate capture efficiency."},{"question":"What makes SUI funding rates different on DEX versus CEX platforms?","answer":"DEX funding rates for SUI often trade at premiums to centralized exchanges due to lower arbitrage capital and different user bases. Orderly's rates tend to be more volatile but can offer higher absolute returns during trending periods."}]}]
